Durban - A man was shot and killed on the N2 highway in Scottburgh, south of Durban on Tuesday. ER24 paramedics responded to the scene of the incident to find another emergency service already in attendance. They also found a wrecked bakkie on its roof on the side of the road, said Russel Meiring, ER24 spokesperson. “Upon closer inspection, paramedics discovered the body of a man lying inside the vehicle. Paramedics assessed the man and found that he had sustained a fatal gunshot wound to his head. Nothing could be done for him and he was declared dead by another service,” said Meiring. He said details surrounding the incident are unknown but police were on scene investigating. Colonel Thembeka Mbhele, police spokesperson said a 45-year-old man was found dead in his Toyota bakkie on the N2 freeway, northbound. “The deceased had gunshot wounds. It is alleged that he was shot whilst driving and he lost control of his bakkie which overturned. The motive of the killing is unknown at this stage. The deceased is a taxi boss from Amandawe affiliated with the Vulamehlo Taxi Association,” said Mbhele. She said a case of murder was opened at Scottburgh police station and it will be transferred to the Provincial Taxi Task Team for investigation. No arrest has been made at this stage. Daily News